So let's talk about a couple of methods of how we can limit log file sizes.

51
00:02:37,720 --> 00:02:42,080
Two major methods that you need to know about, circular overwrite and clipping levels.

52
00:02:42,080 --> 00:02:44,800
Now let's start with circular overwrite.

53
00:02:44,800 --> 00:02:50,160
The way circular overwrite works is you set a maximum log file size or length.

54
00:02:50,160 --> 00:02:56,200
And then you start writing log event data until you reach the maximum file size or the

55
00:02:56,200 --> 00:03:01,120
maximum number of lines and then you circle back to the top and start overwriting.

56
00:03:01,120 --> 00:03:03,520
That's circular overwrite.

57
00:03:03,520 --> 00:03:07,160
And what it means is that your log file size is never ending at larger than the maximum

58
00:03:07,160 --> 00:03:11,880
number of entries or the file size that you set because as soon as you reach that maximum,

59
00:03:11,880 --> 00:03:15,200
you circle back to the top and start overwriting.

60
00:03:15,200 --> 00:03:19,080
The other method you can use is what's known as clipping levels.

61
00:03:19,080 --> 00:03:23,200
When clipping levels is this idea that we set a threshold below that threshold, don't

62
00:03:23,200 --> 00:03:24,720
bother logging anything.

63
00:03:24,720 --> 00:03:27,120
Above that threshold, start logging.

